1
00:00:01,586 --> 00:00:05,073
First, the surgery on Fink,
now the director's arrest.

2
00:00:05,113 --> 00:00:08,080
Our hospital's really famous now.

3
00:00:08,120 --> 00:00:10,605
Not the kind of fame we need.

4
00:00:10,645 --> 00:00:13,800
It sure is quiet without Dr. Ashura around.

5
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:14,920
A conference, right?

6
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:16,167
Apparently so.

7
00:00:16,207 --> 00:00:19,473
Dr. Daikoku, will you be okay on your own?

8
00:00:19,513 --> 00:00:20,727
I'll be fine.

9
00:00:21,027 --> 00:00:23,909
Dr. Bonten will work here from today, too.

10
00:00:24,170 --> 00:00:25,655
Ow, hot!

11
00:00:25,695 --> 00:00:26,756
He doesn't look fine.

12
00:00:26,796 --> 00:00:27,796
Yeah.

13
00:00:27,821 --> 00:00:28,821
Ow!

14
00:00:28,856 --> 00:00:29,856
Huh?

15
00:00:29,896 --> 00:00:33,613
Ow! Ow! It hurts! It hurts so much.

16
00:00:33,653 --> 00:00:35,400
My ear! My ear!

17
00:00:35,440 --> 00:00:36,693
What happened?

18
00:00:36,879 --> 00:00:39,166
He fell off his bike and injured his ear.

19
00:00:39,206 --> 00:00:40,206
His ear?

20
00:00:40,231 --> 00:00:42,716
It's been completely severed.

21
00:00:42,840 --> 00:00:44,500
Take a look at this...

22
00:00:46,706 --> 00:00:47,909
It's his ear.

23
00:00:48,313 --> 00:00:49,786
My ear! My ear!

24
00:00:49,826 --> 00:00:51,080
This won't do.

25
00:00:51,253 --> 00:00:54,346
At room temperature, the tissue will
deteriorate and become unusable.

26
00:00:54,405 --> 00:00:55,840
- What?
- Cool it down immediately.

27
00:00:55,880 --> 00:00:57,091
Yes, Doctor.

28
00:00:57,119 --> 00:01:00,258
Either way, the ER can't handle this.
Let's call Plastic Surgery.

29
00:01:00,298 --> 00:01:02,679
- They're in surgery until tonight.
- What?

30
00:01:02,719 --> 00:01:06,602
The golden time for severed tissue is
about eight hours.

31
00:01:06,642 --> 00:01:10,991
If blood flow isn't restored by then,
reattachment becomes impossible.

32
00:01:11,031 --> 00:01:12,326
We won't make it in time!

33
00:01:12,366 --> 00:01:14,305
No other hospital can take him either.

34
00:01:14,345 --> 00:01:16,469
Hurry up and fix my ear!

35
00:01:16,509 --> 00:01:19,175
At this rate,
this patient's going to lose his ear.

36
00:01:19,215 --> 00:01:22,055
If only Dr. Anno were here...

37
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:25,136
It looks like you need help.

38
00:01:27,690 --> 00:01:31,640
I'll reattach that patient's ear for you.

39
00:01:33,959 --> 00:01:38,329
Dr. Tamon, I want you
to take over as director.

40
00:01:40,687 --> 00:01:45,776
Taishaku could collapse at any moment
as things stand now.

41
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:49,920
You're the only one I can entrust
with this. Please.

42
00:01:53,410 --> 00:01:54,629
Understood.

43
00:01:54,802 --> 00:01:56,016
Thank you.

44
00:01:57,950 --> 00:02:00,755
I'm grateful you accepted.

45
00:02:02,043 --> 00:02:03,378
By the way, Chairwoman...

46
00:02:04,356 --> 00:02:08,043
What do you intend to do
with the ER in this situation?

47
00:02:10,853 --> 00:02:17,116
Now that Fink's donation has been withdrawn
and we've lost funding for the new hospital,

48
00:02:19,403 --> 00:02:21,509
we can't keep the ER open.

49
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:26,663
Let's change emergency medicine
in Japan together.

50
00:02:28,373 --> 00:02:31,446
We'll shut down the ER.

51
00:02:32,972 --> 00:02:34,473
No objections, right?

52
00:02:36,965 --> 00:02:41,643
Abandoning lives right in front of you
for your own goals. You're no different.

53
00:02:47,029 --> 00:02:48,235
Yes.

54
00:02:50,599 --> 00:02:55,630
One more thing. I've decided
to assign Naomi to the ER.

55
00:02:56,203 --> 00:03:03,010
Evenly spaced sutures, perfect technique.
I've never seen anything like it.

56
00:03:03,050 --> 00:03:05,356
She might even be better than Anno.

57
00:03:06,423 --> 00:03:08,485
There, you're all set now.

58
00:03:08,525 --> 00:03:10,459
- Cover it with gauze, please.
- Got it.

59
00:03:10,499 --> 00:03:13,285
Thank you so much.

60
00:03:13,660 --> 00:03:15,510
Glad I could help.

61
00:03:16,313 --> 00:03:19,099
By the way, may I ask who you are?

62
00:03:20,340 --> 00:03:23,540
I'm a plastic surgeon starting here today.

63
00:03:24,673 --> 00:03:26,006
Why the ER?

64
00:03:27,186 --> 00:03:35,030
Before the ER shuts down, I thought
it'd be fun to have her work with Ashura.

65
00:03:37,142 --> 00:03:40,869
Still, gaining two doctors
at once like this...

66
00:03:40,909 --> 00:03:43,976
The ER should run much more smoothly now.

67
00:03:45,889 --> 00:03:47,090
What's wrong?

68
00:03:47,876 --> 00:03:54,482
Dr. Naomi is ready to go from day one,
but like the incident with the ear-cooling,

69
00:03:55,037 --> 00:03:57,010
all I do is hold everyone back.

70
00:03:58,381 --> 00:04:03,482
You just joined the ER.
There's no need to rush.

71
00:04:14,369 --> 00:04:16,102
- Good morning.
- Morning.

72
00:04:16,142 --> 00:04:19,953
- Who's that?
- A plastic surgeon who joined us yesterday.

73
00:04:19,993 --> 00:04:24,935
Dr. Naomi worked
at Crestwood Memorial Hospital in the US.

74
00:04:24,975 --> 00:04:27,296
The top plastic surgery hospital
in America, right?

75
00:04:27,326 --> 00:04:28,746
Why'd she leave?

76
00:04:28,786 --> 00:04:33,450
Yuri asked me to work here.
Ah, the chairwoman is my aunt.

77
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:34,846
Aunt?!

78
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:37,026
So you're related to the chairwoman?!

79
00:04:37,240 --> 00:04:38,440
Yes.

80
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:44,352
Besides, I wanted to work with Dr. Ashura.

81
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:46,840
Wait, you two know each other?

82
00:04:47,620 --> 00:04:48,826
Sort of.

83
00:04:50,453 --> 00:04:56,000
Yuri always said you'd do anything
to save a life.

84
00:04:57,013 --> 00:04:59,113
Fighting like a true Ashura.

85
00:05:01,303 --> 00:05:06,460
But I'll be doing things my own way.

86
00:05:08,713 --> 00:05:10,113
Suit yourself.

87
00:05:31,250 --> 00:05:33,763
Dr. Ashura

88
00:05:34,512 --> 00:05:36,318
My tooth has been hurting
since this morning.

89
00:05:36,358 --> 00:05:37,558
Your tooth?

90
00:05:37,906 --> 00:05:39,520
Could it be a cavity?

91
00:05:39,893 --> 00:05:41,372
Maybe.

92
00:05:41,515 --> 00:05:44,375
You should probably see a dentist about that.

93
00:05:44,814 --> 00:05:48,453
Normally, would anyone come
to the ER just for a toothache?

94
00:05:52,350 --> 00:05:53,623
What's wrong?

95
00:05:55,769 --> 00:05:59,843
I'll prescribe some painkillers.
Please see a dentist soon.

96
00:05:59,850 --> 00:06:02,363
Okay, understood. Thank you very much.

97
00:06:02,403 --> 00:06:03,403
Take care.

98
00:06:03,430 --> 00:06:06,755
Wait. Get an EKG
and echocardiogram ready right away.

99
00:06:06,795 --> 00:06:09,183
Get a blood sample and run a troponin test.

100
00:06:11,503 --> 00:06:12,915
Myocardial infarction?!

101
00:06:12,955 --> 00:06:16,730
Heart attack patients sometimes show
tooth pain rather than chest pain.

102
00:06:16,770 --> 00:06:20,850
But the pain
from a heart attack is excruciating.

103
00:06:20,890 --> 00:06:23,155
He couldn't just walk in normally.

104
00:06:23,195 --> 00:06:25,130
His chart shows a history of diabetes.

105
00:06:28,050 --> 00:06:30,835
Diabetes? What's that got to do with it?

106
00:06:30,875 --> 00:06:35,483
Diabetic neuropathy masked the pain
that should've been debilitating.

107
00:06:36,950 --> 00:06:38,523
He'll go into cardiac arrest.

108
00:06:41,310 --> 00:06:43,050
Doctor, please help me!

109
00:06:43,090 --> 00:06:45,103
Prep for PCI now.
Contact the catheterization lab.

110
00:06:45,143 --> 00:06:46,390
Yes!

111
00:06:53,317 --> 00:06:54,523
Hey.

112
00:06:54,923 --> 00:06:55,960
God Hand.

113
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:57,220
Good to see you.

114
00:06:57,556 --> 00:06:59,423
Good to see you, too.

115
00:07:00,406 --> 00:07:03,743
Never thought you'd end up
in the ER, Dr. Bonten.

116
00:07:03,783 --> 00:07:06,873
I'm sorry for the trouble caused
by my sudden transfer.

117
00:07:06,913 --> 00:07:09,389
Not at all. We're grateful, actually.

118
00:07:09,609 --> 00:07:16,923
VIPs are flooding our surgery department
over rumors that the God Hand is at Taishaku.

119
00:07:18,756 --> 00:07:22,585
I'm sure the brilliant Dr. Bonten has

120
00:07:22,625 --> 00:07:28,296
a 99 percent success rate
in the ER too, right?

121
00:07:30,145 --> 00:07:33,832
By the way, Fink was discharged this morning.

122
00:07:34,005 --> 00:07:36,363
Oh, really?

123
00:07:36,366 --> 00:07:41,160
He believed you were his savior
right until the very end.

124
00:07:41,200 --> 00:07:45,630
Well, good for you. To him,
you'll always be God Hand.

125
00:07:45,710 --> 00:07:50,156
Even though you are just Normal Hand.

126
00:07:56,033 --> 00:07:59,390
The PCI went well. You're in the clear now.

127
00:07:59,776 --> 00:08:02,810
Thank you so much, Doctor.

128
00:08:05,293 --> 00:08:06,502
Doctor?

129
00:08:11,753 --> 00:08:12,986
Incoming.

130
00:08:16,890 --> 00:08:17,968
One, two, three.

131
00:08:18,008 --> 00:08:19,809
Oxygen at four liters.
Ultrasound and X-ray.

132
00:08:19,849 --> 00:08:21,176
I'll get the X-ray.

133
00:08:21,925 --> 00:08:24,605
Why wasn't an IV line started
in the ambulance?

134
00:08:24,645 --> 00:08:26,250
What were you doing in there?

135
00:08:26,290 --> 00:08:30,845
Paramedics are only authorized
to start IV lines on cardiac arrest patients.

136
00:08:30,885 --> 00:08:33,410
I see. It's different from America then.

137
00:08:35,508 --> 00:08:36,508
Ah!

138
00:08:36,536 --> 00:08:38,289
Mitral valve regurgitation.

139
00:08:38,329 --> 00:08:42,489
Heart failure's causing pulmonary congestion.
She needs surgery as soon as possible.

140
00:08:42,663 --> 00:08:46,070
First, treat the pulmonary congestion.
Administer diuretics and vasodilators.

141
00:08:46,110 --> 00:08:49,769
Got it. Ms. Satake,
I'm going to start an IV, okay?

142
00:08:49,890 --> 00:08:51,116
Stop!

143
00:08:55,930 --> 00:08:58,758
It's all right. It'll be over quickly.

144
00:08:58,798 --> 00:09:01,830
I said I don't need that!

145
00:09:04,828 --> 00:09:06,356
I'm leaving.

146
00:09:06,776 --> 00:09:08,310
Please wait!

147
00:09:12,380 --> 00:09:18,350
I was just resting on a bench when someone
unnecessarily called an ambulance for me.

148
00:09:24,770 --> 00:09:27,435
What are you doing? Let go!

149
00:09:27,475 --> 00:09:33,741
Cold hands, tachycardia, cyanosis
in the fingertips. Severe cardiac strain.

150
00:09:35,470 --> 00:09:37,750
You could drop dead at any moment.

151
00:09:44,170 --> 00:09:46,450
I said I don't want treatment!

152
00:09:54,270 --> 00:09:55,550
Ms. Satake!

153
00:09:56,023 --> 00:09:58,223
No need to chase after her.

154
00:09:59,168 --> 00:10:03,523
We explained her medical situation,
and she chose to leave.

155
00:10:03,836 --> 00:10:06,516
This was her own decision.

156
00:10:06,676 --> 00:10:08,829
She'll die without treatment.

157
00:10:08,869 --> 00:10:12,236
Doctors have no right
to force treatment on patients.

158
00:10:14,755 --> 00:10:15,955
"Right?"

159
00:10:16,290 --> 00:10:21,056
Treating a patient against their will could
lead to a lawsuit.

160
00:10:22,077 --> 00:10:26,930
If the hospital gets sued, your actions would
drag all of us down with you.

161
00:10:34,363 --> 00:10:36,530
She is on the battlefield
between life and death.

162
00:10:38,543 --> 00:10:41,603
I can't just abandon
a life right in front of me.

163
00:10:47,060 --> 00:10:48,165
Dr. Anno!

164
00:10:48,205 --> 00:10:49,419
Stop.

165
00:10:50,780 --> 00:10:53,200
Her approach is wrong.

166
00:10:54,500 --> 00:10:56,783
You don't need to get caught up in this.

167
00:10:59,729 --> 00:11:01,582
I'll go check on them.

168
00:11:14,620 --> 00:11:16,791
I told you. You need treatment...

169
00:11:16,831 --> 00:11:18,173
Stop it!

170
00:11:19,180 --> 00:11:22,540
Is there a reason
why you don't want treatment?

171
00:11:26,963 --> 00:11:28,363
There is a reason, right?

172
00:11:33,043 --> 00:11:35,896
I have a violin competition in ten days.

173
00:11:38,219 --> 00:11:42,496
Ms. Satake, you need
at least two weeks of hospitalization.

174
00:11:42,981 --> 00:11:46,626
As for the competition,
you can recover and try the next...

175
00:11:46,666 --> 00:11:48,141
There is no next time!

176
00:11:49,866 --> 00:11:56,056
If I don’t place high enough, I’ll lose
my scholarship and have to drop out!

177
00:11:57,833 --> 00:12:00,493
I have to compete even if it kills me!

178
00:12:01,102 --> 00:12:02,613
I understand.

179
00:12:04,893 --> 00:12:06,533
I'll fix you in one week.

180
00:12:07,049 --> 00:12:08,255
What?

181
00:12:09,733 --> 00:12:12,626
That pain won't go away without treatment.

182
00:12:13,752 --> 00:12:16,313
Can you really perform in this condition?

183
00:12:18,953 --> 00:12:23,750
I will get you ready
for that competition. I promise.

184
00:12:25,693 --> 00:12:29,840
Chasing down a runaway patient...
That's Dr. Ashura for you.

185
00:12:29,880 --> 00:12:33,220
I wish she wouldn't make
extra work for everyone.

186
00:12:33,473 --> 00:12:37,740
It's just self-satisfaction on her part,
and a bother to the patient.

187
00:12:40,006 --> 00:12:44,866
I'm transferring to Surgery.
There's no point staying in the ER.

188
00:12:44,906 --> 00:12:49,952
Hold on. Why not give it a little more time?

189
00:13:01,063 --> 00:13:04,023
Dr. Anno, are you sure about this?

190
00:13:05,263 --> 00:13:07,195
Isn't the competition unrealistic?

191
00:13:07,235 --> 00:13:08,495
I'll make it happen.

192
00:13:08,763 --> 00:13:09,816
But how?

193
00:13:09,856 --> 00:13:11,569
Read this by tomorrow.

194
00:13:16,223 --> 00:13:21,036
MICS? Are you planning to do this surgery?

195
00:13:21,196 --> 00:13:27,690
A standard sternotomy means a large incision
and a longer stay. MICS is faster.

196
00:13:27,730 --> 00:13:31,455
But with MICS, instruments only go through
a small incision,

197
00:13:31,495 --> 00:13:35,483
so the limited visibility makes
this operation far more difficult.

198
00:13:35,570 --> 00:13:37,870
Even you can't pull this off.

199
00:13:38,910 --> 00:13:40,116
There's no other way

200
00:13:42,536 --> 00:13:44,742
to grant her wish.

201
00:13:52,376 --> 00:13:54,043
How may I help you?

202
00:13:54,170 --> 00:13:56,396
It's nothing serious,

203
00:13:57,049 --> 00:14:00,890
but could you keep an eye on things
between Ashura and Naomi?

204
00:14:01,516 --> 00:14:05,249
Did something happen with Anno?

205
00:14:06,463 --> 00:14:10,843
Brilliant doctors are bound
to butt heads, right?

206
00:14:13,290 --> 00:14:14,676
Understood.

207
00:14:17,380 --> 00:14:20,980
We'll now perform
mitral valve repair using MICS.

208
00:14:21,709 --> 00:14:25,042
Dr. Anno, I really think MICS is beyond us.

209
00:14:25,082 --> 00:14:28,533
Let's switch to a standard sternotomy.
The patient will understand.

210
00:14:28,573 --> 00:14:29,826
I made...

211
00:14:32,146 --> 00:14:34,079
a promise to this girl.

212
00:14:41,663 --> 00:14:44,356
- Let's begin. Scalpel.
- Here.

213
00:14:46,950 --> 00:14:48,590
- Electric scalpel.
- Here.

214
00:14:55,696 --> 00:14:57,840
Director, is something the matter?

215
00:14:57,880 --> 00:15:00,713
No, I just happened to be passing by.

216
00:15:04,266 --> 00:15:06,100
It’s rare that Anno isn’t here.

217
00:15:06,140 --> 00:15:08,780
Oh, Dr. Anno is in surgery right now.

218
00:15:08,949 --> 00:15:11,356
An ER doctor doing MICS? It's unheard of.

219
00:15:11,520 --> 00:15:13,783
MICS? Anno?

220
00:15:13,820 --> 00:15:18,660
Yes. There's a patient who absolutely needs
to be discharged quickly.

221
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:20,820
Dr. Anno is wrong.

222
00:15:21,960 --> 00:15:24,433
It doesn't matter what the patient requests.

223
00:15:24,473 --> 00:15:28,713
There's no need to take on extra risk
with a difficult procedure.

224
00:15:29,980 --> 00:15:34,550
Making that call objectively is
part of a doctor's job, isn't it?

225
00:15:37,302 --> 00:15:43,196
Actually, last month,
Anno saved my son's life, too.

226
00:15:45,410 --> 00:15:51,850
That time as well, she deliberately chose
the harder approach for my son's future.

227
00:15:54,380 --> 00:15:57,516
That's the kind of doctor she is.

228
00:16:12,686 --> 00:16:14,746
Exposing the left atrium.
Widen the opening more.

229
00:16:14,786 --> 00:16:16,163
Got it.

230
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:21,313
I can't see. Widen it more.

231
00:16:21,353 --> 00:16:23,072
It's too narrow to get a clear view.

232
00:16:23,112 --> 00:16:27,183
If we push forward and accidentally nick
a vessel, there'll be massive bleeding.

233
00:16:28,623 --> 00:16:31,365
Maybe we really should switch
to standard sternotomy...

234
00:16:31,405 --> 00:16:33,781
Switching to the transseptal approach.
Long Metzenbaum.

235
00:16:33,821 --> 00:16:35,027
Here.

236
00:16:37,386 --> 00:16:38,613
It's okay.

237
00:16:41,106 --> 00:16:42,696
I will make this work.

238
00:16:47,598 --> 00:16:49,559
- Grasping forceps.
- Here.

239
00:16:52,579 --> 00:16:54,205
- Needle holder.
- Here.

240
00:17:04,990 --> 00:17:06,190
Here you go.

241
00:17:22,276 --> 00:17:24,083
You did it. It went through!

242
00:17:24,210 --> 00:17:25,516
Mitral valve reached.

243
00:17:25,556 --> 00:17:27,176
- Needle holder.
- Got it.

244
00:17:30,509 --> 00:17:34,536
We remove the excess leaflet tissue.
Mitral valve repair with the loop technique.

245
00:17:34,576 --> 00:17:35,783
Understood.

246
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:42,170
She's skilled, I'll give her that.

247
00:17:42,510 --> 00:17:45,430
But I don't think she and I will get along.

248
00:17:56,013 --> 00:18:01,186
The surgery was a success.
She should be discharged in a week.

249
00:18:01,273 --> 00:18:03,113
Thank you so much.

250
00:18:07,717 --> 00:18:09,010
Um...

251
00:18:09,783 --> 00:18:15,990
Could it be that you are Dr. Bonten,
the famous God Hand?

252
00:18:20,010 --> 00:18:22,237
Oh... Yes.

253
00:18:22,290 --> 00:18:24,176
I knew it!

254
00:18:24,615 --> 00:18:30,949
My daughter is so lucky to have been
operated on by the great Dr. Bonten.

255
00:18:34,090 --> 00:18:37,976
Why did you choose the MICS procedure?

256
00:18:40,170 --> 00:18:46,776
Failure could cost you the patient’s trust
and maybe even a lawsuit.

257
00:18:47,383 --> 00:18:50,483
Aren't you afraid of failing?

258
00:18:51,510 --> 00:18:53,303
Of course I am.

259
00:18:54,910 --> 00:18:56,570
Then why?

260
00:18:57,849 --> 00:19:00,276
I don't just want to save
the patients' lives.

261
00:19:02,995 --> 00:19:05,203
I want to preserve their whole future.

262
00:19:20,633 --> 00:19:21,843
Doctor!

263
00:19:21,886 --> 00:19:25,170
Oh, Satake! You came?

264
00:19:25,260 --> 00:19:28,340
I wanted to thank everyone before I leave.

265
00:19:32,683 --> 00:19:34,149
Dr. Anno...

266
00:19:35,682 --> 00:19:40,116
Thank you so much
for getting me discharged in just one week.

267
00:19:41,220 --> 00:19:44,016
I just did my job.

268
00:19:44,550 --> 00:19:45,797
Still...

269
00:19:47,043 --> 00:19:49,086
I'm truly grateful.

270
00:19:50,930 --> 00:19:52,170
I thought...

271
00:19:52,502 --> 00:19:58,023
that if I can't play the violin anymore,
my life wouldn't be worth living.

272
00:19:59,846 --> 00:20:04,023
That there was no point in treatment
if I'd miss the competition.

273
00:20:04,960 --> 00:20:11,136
But you performed that difficult surgery
for my sake.

274
00:20:12,725 --> 00:20:14,592
Because of you,

275
00:20:15,725 --> 00:20:19,291
I found the will to keep living.

276
00:20:23,776 --> 00:20:28,443
Thank you for coming after me that day,

277
00:20:29,429 --> 00:20:31,210
and for the surgery.

278
00:20:32,875 --> 00:20:35,161
I'll always be grateful for what you did.

279
00:20:48,240 --> 00:20:49,563
The competition...

280
00:20:52,050 --> 00:20:53,470
Good luck.

281
00:20:56,342 --> 00:20:59,003
I'm definitely going to win.

282
00:21:02,143 --> 00:21:03,676
Well, we should go.

283
00:21:05,283 --> 00:21:06,703
Thank you so much.

284
00:21:06,743 --> 00:21:08,403
Thank you so much.

285
00:21:09,243 --> 00:21:11,149
- Good luck!
- Thank you.

286
00:21:29,643 --> 00:21:32,050
Man, I'm so tired.

287
00:21:34,096 --> 00:21:35,482
So hot!

288
00:21:35,836 --> 00:21:37,043
Hot!

289
00:21:38,201 --> 00:21:39,403
Hm?

290
00:21:53,245 --> 00:21:54,445
Whoa!

291
00:21:55,360 --> 00:21:58,432
What are you doing?! Clean this up now!

292
00:22:04,503 --> 00:22:07,653
No one's willing to lend us money.

293
00:22:07,930 --> 00:22:10,996
Other than shutting down
the emergency department,

294
00:22:11,802 --> 00:22:16,330
there's no way
to make the new hospital happen.

295
00:22:19,030 --> 00:22:24,496
Even if Taishaku closes its ER, there are
other hospitals nearby that have one.

296
00:22:25,956 --> 00:22:29,689
There should be almost no impact on patients.

297
00:22:39,396 --> 00:22:41,860
It's morning already.

298
00:22:41,900 --> 00:22:44,180
Dr. Anno, today's finally the day, isn't it?

299
00:22:44,503 --> 00:22:45,503
What do you mean?

300
00:22:45,531 --> 00:22:47,700
It's the day of Satake's competition.

301
00:22:47,740 --> 00:22:48,940
Oh, right.

302
00:22:54,630 --> 00:22:57,363
It's already noon.

303
00:22:57,476 --> 00:22:58,696
You're still here?

304
00:22:58,742 --> 00:23:00,542
Go home already.

305
00:23:00,650 --> 00:23:01,869
Your shift's over.

306
00:23:01,909 --> 00:23:05,171
In Japan, doctors keep working
after overnight shifts.

307
00:23:05,211 --> 00:23:08,295
Aren't there work hour regulations
like in the US?

308
00:23:08,450 --> 00:23:12,610
They started work-style reforms
for doctors last year,

309
00:23:12,913 --> 00:23:18,406
but you can't cut hours without adding staff,
so there's no way to make the schedule work.

310
00:23:20,016 --> 00:23:22,516
Dr. Anno, you're not going home either?

311
00:23:22,556 --> 00:23:23,601
I'm heading to the ICU.

312
00:23:23,641 --> 00:23:24,783
Now?

313
00:23:24,823 --> 00:23:27,830
The patient's inflammation won't go down.
I need to replace the CV.

314
00:23:28,270 --> 00:23:29,956
Then let me help.

315
00:23:29,996 --> 00:23:31,757
Dr. Yakushiji, go home.

316
00:23:31,829 --> 00:23:32,829
Huh?

317
00:23:32,856 --> 00:23:37,982
The resident can't rest because you,
his superior, keep working like this.

318
00:23:38,130 --> 00:23:42,943
If we don't, treatments keep getting delayed,
and we lose patients we could've saved.

319
00:23:43,710 --> 00:23:46,103
That’s not our fault.

320
00:23:46,583 --> 00:23:50,076
It's the management’s responsibility
to hire enough staff.

321
00:23:50,116 --> 00:23:53,396
That excuse doesn't fly
when patients' lives are at stake.

322
00:23:54,490 --> 00:23:58,056
So you're just going to keep
sacrificing yourself like this?

323
00:23:59,770 --> 00:24:04,442
Dr. Yakushiji, do you think
Dr. Anno is right?

324
00:24:04,482 --> 00:24:05,682
What?

325
00:24:08,956 --> 00:24:10,861
Kid, go home for today.

326
00:24:10,901 --> 00:24:12,180
But there's still work...

327
00:24:12,220 --> 00:24:13,420
I'll handle the rest.

328
00:24:15,490 --> 00:24:17,803
Well, I'll get back to work, too.

329
00:24:21,899 --> 00:24:24,973
This patient's acidosis is progressing.
Administer more sodium bicarbonate.

330
00:24:25,013 --> 00:24:26,332
Understood.

331
00:24:27,846 --> 00:24:30,149
Dr. Ashura, you're still working?

332
00:24:30,426 --> 00:24:32,682
She's always like this.

333
00:24:40,416 --> 00:24:41,616
Incoming.

334
00:24:43,910 --> 00:24:46,330
- Yes.
- Chuo Memorial Hospital requests transfer.

335
00:24:46,350 --> 00:24:50,455
A woman with a severed right arm
from a car accident. They can't handle it.

336
00:24:50,495 --> 00:24:52,070
We'll take her. Bring her in now.

337
00:24:52,543 --> 00:24:54,390
- Prep for surgery.
- Understood.

338
00:25:00,403 --> 00:25:05,289
Let's shut down the ER quickly
and make this happen.

339
00:25:05,403 --> 00:25:06,990
Director Tamon... No, that's not it.

340
00:25:07,030 --> 00:25:12,610
Once Director Tamon becomes head
of the new hospital, this one goes to me...

341
00:25:12,650 --> 00:25:14,436
- Your phone is ringing...
- Oh, the phone.

342
00:25:14,476 --> 00:25:16,317
Yes. Excuse me.

343
00:25:16,357 --> 00:25:17,423
Yes?

344
00:25:17,463 --> 00:25:20,130
Huh? Plastic surgery?

345
00:25:20,202 --> 00:25:25,396
I see. Leave it to yours truly,
Matayoshi Kongo. I'm ready to...

346
00:25:26,595 --> 00:25:31,243
An amputation? No way I'm free.
I've got surgeries till tonight.

347
00:25:32,270 --> 00:25:35,450
That's not my problem.
Stop calling me about this.

348
00:25:37,976 --> 00:25:43,143
It's the ER again. Apparently,
a patient came in with a severed right arm.

349
00:25:43,149 --> 00:25:44,823
- A severed arm?
- Yes.

350
00:25:44,830 --> 00:25:48,730
That plastic surgeon from America
left right when her shift ended.

351
00:25:49,062 --> 00:25:53,116
But without a plastic surgeon,
replantation would be impossible, right?

352
00:25:53,156 --> 00:25:58,350
Exactly. I bet Ashura forced them
to accept a patient again.

353
00:25:58,433 --> 00:26:01,149
I feel sorry for the patient
who's going to lose their arm.

354
00:26:05,169 --> 00:26:06,369
Huh?

355
00:26:08,995 --> 00:26:11,375
Dr. Naomi, what are you doing here?

356
00:26:11,660 --> 00:26:14,126
What do you mean? I'm going home, obviously.

357
00:26:14,166 --> 00:26:19,286
A patient with a severed right arm was
transferred here because they couldn't help.

358
00:26:19,585 --> 00:26:21,980
They want us there immediately for surgery.

359
00:26:22,120 --> 00:26:24,080
My shift is over.

360
00:26:24,793 --> 00:26:28,965
You're the only one in the ER
who can do a replantation!

361
00:26:29,005 --> 00:26:35,000
The staff shortage isn't my fault.
Dr. Ashura's there. The patient will live.

362
00:26:35,199 --> 00:26:36,439
See you.

363
00:26:37,851 --> 00:26:40,371
The patient is Satake!

364
00:26:46,300 --> 00:26:50,820
And you still think just saving
her life is enough?

365
00:27:00,556 --> 00:27:03,203
It doesn't matter who the patient is.

366
00:27:04,395 --> 00:27:08,489
A doctor should treat every patient equally.

367
00:27:08,748 --> 00:27:10,283
You're right...

368
00:27:12,309 --> 00:27:13,976
That may be true.

369
00:27:15,210 --> 00:27:19,563
But I can't accept Satake losing her arm.

370
00:27:20,763 --> 00:27:25,116
I want her to be able
to keep playing the violin.

371
00:27:26,795 --> 00:27:32,156
Even without you, Dr. Naomi,
Dr. Anno and I will manage somehow.

372
00:27:51,737 --> 00:27:53,737
No need to chase after her.

373
00:27:53,903 --> 00:27:57,836
There's no need to take on extra risk
with a difficult procedure.

374
00:27:57,876 --> 00:28:02,176
Thank you for coming after me that day,
and for the surgery.

375
00:28:02,395 --> 00:28:04,416
I'll always be grateful for what you did.

376
00:28:19,222 --> 00:28:22,649
I'll perform stump closure.
Kid, release the tourniquet.

377
00:28:22,770 --> 00:28:28,076
Stump closure... You mean
you're sealing the wound?

378
00:28:28,630 --> 00:28:32,670
Why? With your skills,
you could reattach the arm, couldn't you?

379
00:28:32,916 --> 00:28:36,916
- The arm hasn't arrived yet.
- What?

380
00:28:36,956 --> 00:28:41,229
The impact flung it away,
so it took time to find it.

381
00:28:41,269 --> 00:28:44,035
It's on its way by ambulance now.

382
00:28:44,256 --> 00:28:47,262
No time. We give up the arm.

383
00:29:02,369 --> 00:29:03,569
Wait.

384
00:29:06,495 --> 00:29:10,375
As soon as the arm arrives,
I'll perform the replantation.

385
00:29:12,423 --> 00:29:15,663
I won't let her lose that arm.

386
00:29:16,663 --> 00:29:18,330
Her life over the arm.

387
00:29:20,190 --> 00:29:22,363
She's a violinist.

388
00:29:23,029 --> 00:29:26,530
That's why you performed
MICS surgery on her, right?

389
00:29:26,570 --> 00:29:28,243
I told you. We can't wait any longer.

390
00:29:28,283 --> 00:29:32,637
Yes, we can. The bleeding
and vitals are under control.

391
00:29:33,090 --> 00:29:36,141
This single decision could
change this girl's entire life.

392
00:29:36,181 --> 00:29:40,469
That's exactly why I made this call.
Choosing the arm means she dies.

393
00:29:42,163 --> 00:29:44,543
Wait... No way.

394
00:29:47,429 --> 00:29:49,556
Dr. Naomi, look at this.

395
00:29:52,687 --> 00:29:55,997
A pseudoaneurysm. Traumatic.

396
00:29:56,280 --> 00:29:58,860
It could rupture at any moment.

397
00:30:00,100 --> 00:30:01,966
The right arm has arrived.

398
00:30:02,113 --> 00:30:03,760
- Here you go.
- Got it.

399
00:30:05,192 --> 00:30:08,231
If we operate now, we can reattach the arm...

400
00:30:08,271 --> 00:30:10,840
- Doctor!
- Ma'am, please wait outside.

401
00:30:10,939 --> 00:30:16,689
Doctor, please, I'm begging you.
Please reattach my daughter's arm.

402
00:30:17,273 --> 00:30:22,283
The violin means as much
to her as life itself.

403
00:30:25,765 --> 00:30:27,471
We can't reattach the arm.

404
00:30:31,236 --> 00:30:35,743
If the aneurysm ruptures during replantation,
she'll die from the shock.

405
00:30:37,570 --> 00:30:40,155
Then why not operate on the aneurysm first?

406
00:30:40,195 --> 00:30:43,875
Her aneurysm is already massive.
Even rushing, it'd take seven hours.

407
00:30:44,909 --> 00:30:47,716
It's been four hours
since her arm was severed.

408
00:30:48,290 --> 00:30:52,710
After the aneurysm surgery,
we'd miss the eight-hour golden time.

409
00:30:53,182 --> 00:30:54,395
No...

410
00:30:54,430 --> 00:30:55,950
To save her life,

411
00:30:57,656 --> 00:30:59,570
we have to give up the arm.

412
00:31:00,569 --> 00:31:07,936
Doctor, isn't there anything you can do?
Please, I'm begging you.

413
00:31:07,976 --> 00:31:11,043
The aneurysm could rupture at any moment.

414
00:31:15,299 --> 00:31:18,012
Saving her life takes priority
over everything.

415
00:31:22,429 --> 00:31:23,629
Please leave.

416
00:31:29,369 --> 00:31:30,576
Ma'am...

417
00:31:55,310 --> 00:31:57,196
Are you sure about this?

418
00:32:09,720 --> 00:32:14,903
Anno, no other ER doctor matches your skill.

419
00:32:17,646 --> 00:32:19,430
And Dr. Rikudo...

420
00:32:20,639 --> 00:32:25,169
No other plastic surgeon matches your skills.

421
00:32:27,933 --> 00:32:35,490
With both of you here, it's a shame
that this is the only option you can see.

422
00:33:05,320 --> 00:33:06,917
Get ready in three minutes.

423
00:33:08,720 --> 00:33:10,613
Two will be plenty.

424
00:33:12,636 --> 00:33:14,542
- Let's go to the OR.
- Yes!

425
00:33:16,326 --> 00:33:19,859
Performing exploratory thoracotomy
for a thoracic pseudoaneurysm.

426
00:33:19,899 --> 00:33:23,559
Performing replantation surgery
for the right forearm amputation.

427
00:33:23,599 --> 00:33:24,812
Yes!

428
00:33:25,359 --> 00:33:26,712
- Scalpel.
- Scalpel.

429
00:33:27,773 --> 00:33:30,819
Simultaneous surgery on the aneurysm
and the arm.

430
00:33:30,932 --> 00:33:31,937
Electric scalpel.

431
00:33:31,977 --> 00:33:33,210
- Irrigation.
- Right.

432
00:33:43,105 --> 00:33:44,689
- One more.
- Got it.

433
00:33:50,826 --> 00:33:52,556
- Rib spreader.
- Here.

434
00:33:58,149 --> 00:34:00,802
- Bone holding forceps for bone shortening.
- Here.

435
00:34:01,609 --> 00:34:02,969
- Gauze.
- Here.

436
00:34:14,463 --> 00:34:15,663
Found it.

437
00:34:16,283 --> 00:34:19,322
Doctor, it's bigger than it looked on the CT.

438
00:34:19,362 --> 00:34:20,930
It could rupture at any moment.

439
00:34:20,970 --> 00:34:22,115
We need to act fast.

440
00:34:22,155 --> 00:34:24,782
- Let's clamp the base to prevent rupture.
- Yes.

441
00:34:24,822 --> 00:34:26,221
- Satinsky clamp.
- Here.

442
00:34:27,550 --> 00:34:30,883
The slightest nick will cause
massive bleeding.

443
00:34:51,230 --> 00:34:55,209
You did it, the clamp's in place.
Bleeding's under control.

444
00:34:56,765 --> 00:35:00,043
We're not done.
The aneurysm extends into the abdomen.

445
00:35:00,083 --> 00:35:01,428
- What?
- Opening the abdomen now.

446
00:35:01,468 --> 00:35:02,907
- Scalpel.
- Here.

447
00:35:10,826 --> 00:35:12,066
Incredible.

448
00:35:12,943 --> 00:35:15,081
Such incredibly delicate work.

449
00:35:49,395 --> 00:35:50,609
Done.

450
00:35:50,949 --> 00:35:52,342
It's over.

451
00:35:53,376 --> 00:35:54,783
Great work.

452
00:35:59,140 --> 00:36:00,483
This girl...

453
00:36:02,279 --> 00:36:03,678
I'll leave the rest to you.

454
00:36:06,523 --> 00:36:08,816
Who do you think I am?

455
00:36:10,343 --> 00:36:14,656
I will reattach this girl's arm.
I guarantee it.

456
00:36:20,450 --> 00:36:21,683
I'm counting on you.

457
00:36:50,442 --> 00:36:51,656
I'll assist.

458
00:36:52,183 --> 00:36:54,346
Thanks. Could you cut the sutures?

459
00:36:54,426 --> 00:36:55,626
Yes.

460
00:36:59,006 --> 00:37:03,593
Dr. Naomi's surgery lasted a full ten hours.

461
00:37:28,503 --> 00:37:30,916
It's been a while since I went all out,

462
00:37:32,430 --> 00:37:33,636
so I'm exhausted.

463
00:37:41,670 --> 00:37:42,876
I see.

464
00:37:45,783 --> 00:37:46,983
Good work.

465
00:37:48,090 --> 00:37:49,850
You too, Dr. Ashura.

466
00:37:51,723 --> 00:37:53,263
Good work.

467
00:38:35,116 --> 00:38:36,930
Oh. What's the matter?

468
00:38:38,503 --> 00:38:41,803
About yesterday... I'm truly...

469
00:38:43,377 --> 00:38:45,063
I'm sorry.

470
00:38:45,357 --> 00:38:46,576
What?

471
00:38:47,383 --> 00:38:48,683
I said...

472
00:38:50,637 --> 00:38:52,603
something so presumptuous to you.

473
00:38:54,136 --> 00:38:56,043
Oh, give me a break.

474
00:38:57,156 --> 00:39:01,836
I came back yesterday as a favor,
but don't expect it to happen again.

475
00:39:06,003 --> 00:39:10,216
Anyway, I'm glad that girl made it through.

476
00:39:13,460 --> 00:39:20,590
I also wanted to give that girl
a chance to play the violin again.

477
00:39:27,440 --> 00:39:31,880
But that doesn't mean I approve
of Dr. Ashura's methods.

478
00:39:35,122 --> 00:39:36,862
This was a one-time thing.

479
00:39:37,710 --> 00:39:38,923
Yes.

480
00:39:41,069 --> 00:39:42,275
See you.

481
00:39:51,009 --> 00:39:56,003
Who'd have thought that Ashura
and Naomi would do a dual surgery together?

482
00:39:56,590 --> 00:40:00,610
The patient was transferred here
after other hospitals couldn't handle it.

483
00:40:01,150 --> 00:40:02,783
Is that so?

484
00:40:02,910 --> 00:40:08,490
Our ER saved a patient
that no other hospital could treat.

485
00:40:10,430 --> 00:40:17,936
This is the result of your efforts
to gather top doctors and save lives.

486
00:40:18,743 --> 00:40:21,356
It's thanks to the staff on the front lines.

487
00:40:25,230 --> 00:40:26,450
Chairwoman.

488
00:40:28,336 --> 00:40:32,289
You actually wanted to keep
the ER open, didn't you?

489
00:40:34,530 --> 00:40:38,070
Isn't that why you assigned
Dr. Rikudo to the ER?

490
00:40:39,469 --> 00:40:41,136
Who knows?

491
00:40:42,849 --> 00:40:44,229
Chairwoman,

492
00:40:46,729 --> 00:40:50,136
would you reverse the decision
to close the ER?

493
00:40:52,569 --> 00:40:59,469
Watching Anno
and the others made me realize I was wrong.

494
00:41:01,263 --> 00:41:05,016
Taishaku needs its emergency department.

495
00:41:06,730 --> 00:41:09,663
Please let me find a way to keep it open.

496
00:41:23,836 --> 00:41:29,803
All right. We'll find a way
to keep the ER open.

497
00:41:31,623 --> 00:41:32,636
Thank you.

498
00:41:32,676 --> 00:41:35,436
But it won't be easy.

499
00:41:38,050 --> 00:41:40,596
It'll be a difficult road ahead.

500
00:42:03,309 --> 00:42:08,396
What do you want now? I still haven't
accepted the closure of the ER.

501
00:42:09,290 --> 00:42:12,929
That's exactly
what I want to talk to you about.

502
00:42:15,590 --> 00:42:17,990
Fink just contacted us.

503
00:42:18,670 --> 00:42:22,550
He'll donate on the condition
that the ER stays open.

504
00:42:25,137 --> 00:42:26,343
What do you mean?

505
00:42:27,223 --> 00:42:32,156
Bonten told Fink that you were
the one who performed his surgery.

506
00:42:33,250 --> 00:42:37,143
Fink wanted to preserve the ER
that saved his life.

507
00:42:40,423 --> 00:42:41,629
I see.

508
00:42:46,820 --> 00:42:51,249
Thanks to you, we don't have to close the ER.

509
00:42:52,286 --> 00:42:56,086
I just wanted to save
the life in front of me.

510
00:42:58,806 --> 00:43:00,006
And...

511
00:43:03,635 --> 00:43:05,790
I wanted to keep a promise.

512
00:43:18,836 --> 00:43:20,476
I was wrong.

513
00:43:23,660 --> 00:43:27,383
As director, I intend to rebuild the ER.

514
00:43:29,560 --> 00:43:34,883
We'll save lives through emergency care
and unite to secure our patients' futures.

515
00:43:40,019 --> 00:43:41,283
Anno.

516
00:43:43,386 --> 00:43:44,876
Lend me your strength.

517
00:43:52,243 --> 00:43:53,456
I will!

518
00:44:09,785 --> 00:44:10,785
Next Episode Preview

519
00:44:10,810 --> 00:44:12,420
Letting a resident do this?!

520
00:44:12,460 --> 00:44:13,840
I'm sorry.

521
00:44:14,100 --> 00:44:16,659
I'm just a resident, and yet...

522
00:44:16,699 --> 00:44:18,243
I think we should downsize.

523
00:44:18,293 --> 00:44:20,513
I'm not going to make it.

524
00:44:20,580 --> 00:44:22,040
Colder than I expected.

525
00:44:22,120 --> 00:44:24,900
Whether to quit or continue is not
for others to decide.
